            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#martaf #AA">
                <p>Klaudia Rosskia while alive made (this) for herself and her relatives. In peace.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it" resp="#martaf">
                <p>Klaudia Rosskia mentre era viva realizz&#242; (questo) per lei e per i suoi parenti. In pace.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>This Christian epitaph presents the structure with the name of the deceased and the verb <foreign xml:lang="grc">&#960;&#959;&#953;&#941;&#969;</foreign> indicating that the deceased, while still alive (participle of <foreign xml:lang="grc">&#950;&#940;&#969;</foreign>), built the monument (or composed the epigram on the monument) for herself and his relatives (on the same structure in Catania see IG 14.489 = <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic001312">ISic001312</ref> and Korhonen 2004: 88-89). The clause <foreign xml:lang="grc">&#956;&#949;&#964;&#8048; &#949;&#7984;&#961;&#942;&#957;&#951;&#962;</foreign> is not frequent, more frequently attested is <foreign xml:lang="grc">&#7952;&#957; &#949;&#7984;&#961;&#942;&#957;&#8131;</foreign> (see IG 14.556 = <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic001375">ISic001375</ref>). The gentilicium <foreign xml:lang="grc">&#8172;&#969;&#963;&#954;&#943;&#945;</foreign> reveals the Roman citizenship of the deceased (for other evidence of the gentilicium in inscriptions from Catania, see IG 14.486 = <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic001309">ISic001309</ref>, IG 14.500 = <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic001321">ISic001321</ref>, IG 14.1981 = <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic003252">ISic003252</ref>).</p>
            </div>
